        <name>7.4.2.3 Which 2 x 2 matrix has an inverse?</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following matrices are invertible? Find the inverse where possible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(A = {@A@}\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(B = {@B@}\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(C = {@C@}\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(D = {@D@}\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(E = {@E@}\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Recall that a \(2 \times 2\) has an inverse if and only if its determinant is nonzero.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;The determinant of \(A = {@A@}\) is \(\lvert A \rvert = {@detWithSteps(A)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(A),simp)@} \neq 0\). Therefore, \(A\) is &lt;b&gt;invertible&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;The determinant of \(B = {@B@}\) is \(\lvert B \rvert = {@detWithSteps(B)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(B),simp)@} \neq 0\). Therefore, \(B\) is &lt;b&gt;invertible&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;The determinant of \(C = {@C@}\) is \(\lvert C \rvert = {@detWithSteps(C)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(C),simp)@}\). Therefore, \(C\) is &lt;b&gt;not invertible&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;The determinant of \(D = {@D@}\) is \(\lvert D \rvert = {@detWithSteps(D)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(D),simp)@} \neq 0\). Therefore, \(D\) is &lt;b&gt;invertible&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;The determinant of \(E = {@E@}\) is \(\lvert E \rvert = {@detWithSteps(E)@} = {@ev(detWithSteps(E),simp)@}\). Therefore, \(E\) is &lt;b&gt;not invertible&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
